=80=99s a bit more likely that Kelce =0Awill score. So the sportsbooks have=
 correlation desks:=0A=0AThe parlay craze got its start in the U.S. when Fl=
utter Entertainment imported =0Aone of its hottest products in Australia. P=
arlays=E2=80=94known as =E2=80=9Cmultis=E2=80=9D in =0AAustralia=E2=80=94ha=
d been available for betting on multiple events. Then a bettor =0Aasked Flu=
tter=E2=80=99s brand in Australia, Sportsbet, why he couldn=E2=80=99t place=
 a multileg =0Abet on a single sporting event.=0A=0AFlutter and Sportsbet b=
egan an effort to crack the math needed to fulfill that =0Arequest. The mat=
h quickly becomes more complicated in a single game because of =0Athe knock=
-on effects of how athletes perform. How well a quarterback throws the =0Ab=
all in a game, for example, affects the performances of a wide receiver =0A=
catching the quarterback=E2=80=99s passes.=0A=0AIn 2016, Sportsbet launched=
 a new product that allowed customers to make =0Asingle-event parlays. Thre=
e years later, Flutter introduced the same product in =0Athe U.S. on FanDue=
l as the =E2=80=9Csame-game parlay.=E2=80=9D=0A=0A=E2=80=9CEverything needs=
 to be connected to everything else, so the math is complex,=E2=80=9D =0Asa=
id Conor Farren, FanDuel senior vice president of sports product and pricin=
g.=0A=0AOne popular explanation of the 2008 financial crisis is, roughly, =
=E2=80=9Cmortgage =0Abond investors underestimated correlations <>,=E2=80=
=9D and as sports gambling becomes =0Aan increasingly huge part of the econ=
omy I look forward to the next =0Acorrelation-based financial crisis.=0A=0A=
