 decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">If you publish words on the internet, you have some proprietary righ=
ts to them. If somebody else just took my columns and republished them, und=
er their own name, without credit to me, and sold ads or subscriptions agai=
nst them, I would be annoyed. If somebody stole my ideas and changed the wo=
rding a little, and then republished them in slightly modified form, I woul=
d be equally =E2=80=94=C2=A0maybe more =E2=80=94=C2=A0annoyed. And so I hav=
e a lot of sympathy for publishers and writers<a href=3D"#footnote-1" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]<=
/span> </a>=C2=A0who say: =E2=80=9CLook, our words are on the internet. It =
seems that OpenAI and other artificial intelligence companies trained their=
 large language models on a corpus of text that includes our words. Effecti=
vely what they are doing is remixing our content for their own commercial p=
urposes. This has the potential to destroy our livelihood =E2=80=94=C2=A0if=
 people go to an AI chatbot for information, instead of to a newspaper or a=
 financial columnist =E2=80=94=C2=A0and has also made the AI people extreme=
ly wealthy. They should have to pay us!=E2=80=9D</li> <li style=3D"margin-b=
ottom: 5px;">If you publish words on the internet, people can read them! If=
 you put your ideas out into the world, you should expect =E2=80=94=C2=A0ho=
pe =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they will influence people. My columns are influence=
d by the ideas and reporting of other people: I learn stuff by reading, and=
 the stuff that I learn goes into what I write. My writing style, similarly=
, is influenced (consciously and unconsciously) by other writing that I rea=
d. The way I write is that there is a network of=C2=A0neurons in my brain t=
hat takes inputs (words I read, etc.) and produces outputs (words I type). =
I do not pay royalties to all the people whose work I read, or ask them for=
 permission to think about their ideas. That=E2=80=99s just the way discour=
se works. And so I have a lot of sympathy for AI companies who say: =E2=80=
=9CLook, we have trained a sort of artificial brain to read all the words i=
n the world, think about them, and then produce its=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>=
writing in response to questions. Our artificial brain has ideas that it ex=
presses in language, and those ideas and that language are influenced by th=
e words that it has read, but that=E2=80=99s true of all writing. If we wer=
e <em>directly plagiarizing</em>=C2=A0other people=E2=80=99s=C2=A0work, tha=
t would be bad, but we=E2=80=99re not. We are just=C2=A0<em>influenced=C2=
=A0</em>by their work, and you can=E2=80=99t sue us for that.=E2=80=9D</li>=
 </ol> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some factual disputes here =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0how close does the large language model come to someone else=
=E2=80=99s copyrighted work, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but mostly there is a phil=
osophical disagreement. Does an LLM mostly remix existing text, or does it =
mostly <em>learn=C2=A0</em>from existing text and generate new text=3F Or a=
re those are the same thing=3F</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively=
 this seems like=C2=A0a dispute between humans who write and publish words,=
 on the one side, and companies that build AI text generation models, on th=
e other side. But that is not inevitable: It=C2=A0is just a fact about the =
present moment, or rather it is a fact about a week ago. In the future, the=
 dispute will be between companies that built AI models that=C2=A0generated=
 outputs, on the one side, and companies that build AI models that=C2=A0<a =
